Belgium is starting Phase 3 of the phase-out plan starting on June 8th 2020. The hospitality industry will be allowed to open partially (gaming halls, banqueting and reception halls will not be allowed to reopen until 1 July).  Banqueting and reception halls will be allowed to operate with a maximum of 50 people present. Nightclubs are not allowed to open before the end of August, as no safety distance can be ensured.

In addition to these exceptions, all other hospitality establishments such as cafes, bars and restaurants will reopen according to a very precise protocol. The main features of this protocol include:

    A distance of 1.50 metres between the tables;
    A maximum of 10 persons per table;
    Each customer must remain seated at their own table;
    Waiters have to wear masks;
    All hospitality establishments are allowed to remain open until one o "clock in the morning, just like the night shops

n Belgium as of June 8th, religious ceremonies may be resumed subject to the following: 

-Safety distances must be observed with a maximum of 100 persons;
-As of July, this number will be increased to 200, just like in the cultural and sports industries;
-Rituals with physical contact are still not allowed.

On April 9 in France, the Agence Fran "aise de D "veloppement launched  "COVID-19  " Health in Common "  " a  "1.2 billion initiative in response to the worldwide public health crisis caused by the COVID-19 pandemic." The initiative is the result of a collaboration between the French President and his African peers and prioritizes "the 19 priority countries for French aid in Africa, the ocean basins (Madagascar, Comoros and Haiti) and the Middle East. 

The main objectives of the initiative are the following:
(1) Reinforcing regional epidemiological surveillance networks;
(2) Contributing to national COVID-19 response plans in African countries;
(3) Supporting the main French actors in the response to COVID-19 (NGOs, foundations, networks, research bodies, etc.);
(4) Providing budget support for the reinforcement of healthcare systems.

